  "text": "Immune Cell Activation following RFA. Recent findings have reported that circulating histones can stimulate innate immune cells (e.g., neutrophils, monocyte/macrophages) to release toxic mediators such as MPO [CITATION_1] , which further aggravates systemic inflammation and tissue injuries. So we assayed circulating MPO activity to check the changes of immune cell activation during RFA. As compared to pre-RFA (median value, 429.6 U/ml; range, 219.4-786.9), there was a significantly enhanced MPO activity in post-RFA lung cancer patients (median value, 1519.4 U/ml; range, 920.1-2336.2; Figure 2 ). Furthermore, there was a clear correlation between circulating histones and MPO ( = 0.4172, = 0.019), supporting that histone-triggered immune cell activation is involved with RFA.",
